Artifacts are definitionally designed by human intent, not directly by evolution. With these intentional acts of authored human creation4 comes not only human responsibility, but an entirely different landscape of potential rewards and design constraints (Bryson et al., 2017; Bryson, 2018). Given all of the above, AGI is obviously a myth—in fact, two orthogonal myths:
- no amount of natural or artificial intelligence will be able to solve all problems;
- even extremely powerful AI is exceedingly unlikely to be very human-like, because it will embody an entirely different set of motivations and reward functions.

